Proposal:

Everyday ggplot2 extension: New approaches to light-weight ‘geom’ extension

Creating new layers (geom_* functions) in ggplot2 extension has been described as an ‘involved process’. While new educational material has lowered the conceptual barrier to entry, the amount of scaffolding code required for classical extension can make regularly using extension feel prohibitive. In this talk, I’ll discuss strategies and tools to make experimentation with new functionality more light-weight and fun. A few practical applications in statistics pedagogy will be presented.

Step 1.

compute_panel_support <- function(data, scales){
  
  data |>
    summarize(xend = max(x),
              x = min(x),
              yend = 0,
              y = 0)
  
}

Step 2.

StatSupport <- ggproto(`_class` = "StatSupport",
                       `_inherit` = ggplot2::Stat,
                       compute_panel = compute_panel_support,
                       required_aes = "x")

Step 3.

geom_support <- function (mapping = NULL, data = NULL, 
                          geom = "segment", position = "identity", 
                          ..., show.legend = NA, inherit.aes = TRUE) 
{
    layer(data = data, mapping = mapping, stat = StatSupport, 
        geom = geom, position = position, show.legend = show.legend, 
        inherit.aes = inherit.aes, params = rlang::list2(na.rm = FALSE, 
            ...))
}

New approach, w {statexpress}

Step 1. Compute

compute_panel_support <- function(data, scales){
  
  data |>
    summarize(xend = max(x),
              x = min(x),
              yend = 0,
              y = 0)
  
}

Step 1.5 Sketch

library(statexpress)

donor |> 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = decision) +
  geom_bar(width = .2) + 
  # sketching geom_support
  qlayer(stat = qstat_panel(compute_panel_support), 
         geom = GeomSegment)

statexpress::qstat_panel - define panel-wise computation for a temp stat. statexpress::qlayer - use a more filled-in version of layer

Step 2. User-facing function

geom_support <- function(...){
  
  qlayer(stat = qstat_panel(compute_panel_support), 
         geom = GeomSegment, ...)
  
}

Extending the right way…

multi-step process, and verbose

gapminder::gapminder %>% 
  filter(country %in% c("United States", "Germany", "United Kingdom", "France", "Canada")) %>% 
  mutate(life_exp_rank = rank(lifeExp), .by = year) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = year, 
      y = life_exp_rank, 
      group = country) + 
  # geom_line() + 
  geom_point() +
  aes(color = country)

compute_panel_rank <- function(data, scales, flip = F){
  
  data %>% 
  group_by(x) %>% 
  mutate(y = rank(rank_var*!flip))
  
}
  
gapminder::gapminder %>% 
  filter(country %in% 
           c("United States", "Germany", "United Kingdom", 
             "France", "Canada")) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = year, rank_var = lifeExp, group = country) + 
  # geom_ranktrack
  geom_line(stat = statexpress::qstat_panel(compute_panel_rank), flip = F) + 
  geom_point(stat = statexpress::qstat_panel(compute_panel_rank), flip = F) +
  aes(color = country)
